Many refugees don't have and cannot get passports. So they have to use people smugglers to get out of their countries and hopefully to somewhere safe. Often it is the people smugglers who decide which country those seeking asylum are taken to. People are passed from agent to agent, some not even knowing where they are, or where they are heading. The people smugglers don't get paid until the person gets to the destination. People have been forced into boats at gunpoint or knifepoint. So not all who come here actually choose to do so.

Those that do choose, usually do so because they have family here, they have a community or cultural links, they speak English, they believe the UK is a fair, tolerant country, where they will be truly safe, able to work and rebuild their lives.

If the UK was one of those first safe countries you are talking about, and we had nearly 4 million refugees like Turkey, would you honestly be so keen on this mythical idea of the first safe country? I seriously doubt it. Why should a country's geographical position decide whether or not it helps those seeking asylum? And they aren't nearly all men. In 2020, 58% of asylum applications were from men of all ages, 42% were from women and children. In 2019, it was 53% and 47%.

There are 26.9 million refugees and 4.4 million people seeking asylum worldwide. 86% do stay in countries neighbouring their own. These are mainly poor, developing countries, with few resources. They are hosting literally hundreds of thousands, millions of refugees. Conditions are beyond grim for most refugees, with no hope of change and improvement.

Unsurprisingly,
a minority travel on, usually those with connections elsewhere, like family, community, cultural links, language, and also the money to pay for the journey.

So only a minority come to Europe, and of those who do, only between 6% - 8% come to the UK. The rest stay in mainland Europe. We take a tiny, tiny proportion of the world's refugees. BBC.COM
Fans to return to Scottish stadiums next week
